on-plans\"><img src=\"http://swagtoolkit.test/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/icon-toolkit.svg\" alt=\"Toolkit\" class=\"wp-image-27\"/></a></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"className\":\"button\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center button\"><a href=\"/lesson-plans\">Go To The Toolkit</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"className\":\"button\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center button\"><a href=\"#about\">Learn More</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:acf/homemap {\n    \"id\": \"block_5ea7ccb71bb45\",\n    \"name\": \"acf\\/homemap\",\n    \"data\": {\n        \"title\": \"Project Summary\",\n        \"_title\": \"field_5ea7cbc1a4736\",\n        \"paragraph\": \"Baltimore, MD and Jackson, MS are two cities where Black men have a particularly high risk of acquiring HIV, and are disproportionately impacted by social determinants when living with HIV.\",\n        \"_paragraph\": \"field_5ea7ee182cc97\",\n        \"map\": 50,\n        \"_map\": \"field_5ea7ee2f2cc98\"\n    },\n    \"mode\": \"edit\"\n} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:acf/homspacial {\n    \"id\": \"block_5eaa7bd964bfe\",\n    \"name\": \"acf\\/homspacial\",\n    \"data\": {\n        \"title\": \"SPATIAL & SOCIOECONOMIC FACTORS\",\n        \"_title\": \"field_5eaa7b18baafb\",\n        \"paragraph\": \"The Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) has recognized that Black men who have sex with men (MSM) living in the American South experience compounding burdens to their wellness. This includes a lack of access to adequate medical care, homophobia, racism, and social support. These matters are exacerbated when the man lives with HIV.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe CDC found rates of HIV diagnosis are the highest in the South (2015). Furthermore, of any region and population in the country, people of color in the South experience the worst clinical outcomes following a positive HIV diagnosis (2016). Baltimore, MD and Jackson, MS are tw