"paragraph\": \"Baltimore, MD and Jackson, MS are two cities where Black men have a particularly high risk of acquiring HIV, and are disproportionately impacted by social determinants when living with HIV.\",\n        \"_paragraph\": \"field_5ea7ee182cc97\",\n        \"map\": 50,\n        \"_map\": \"field_5ea7ee2f2cc98\"\n    },\n    \"mode\": \"edit\"\n} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:acf/homspacial {\n    \"id\": \"block_5eaa7bd964bfe\",\n    \"name\": \"acf\\/homspacial\",\n    \"data\": {\n        \"title\": \"SPATIAL & SOCIOECONOMIC FACTORS\",\n        \"_title\": \"field_5eaa7b18baafb\",\n        \"paragraph\": \"The Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) has recognized that Black men who have sex with men (MSM) living in the American South experience compounding burdens to their wellness. This includes a lack of access to adequate medical care, homophobia, racism, and social support. These matters are exacerbated when the man lives with HIV.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe CDC found rates of HIV diagnosis are the highest in the South (<em>2015<\\/em>). Furthermore, of any region and population in the country, people of color in the South experience the worst clinical outcomes following a positive HIV diagnosis (<em>2016<\\/em>). Baltimore, MD and Jackson, MS are two cities where Black men have a very high risk of acquiring HIV (<em>Oster et al., 2011; Mena &amp; Crosby, 2017<\\/em>).\\r\\n\\r\\nFor these reasons, there is an urgent need to understand the various prevention and education needs that impact the sexual well-being and decision-making of Black men in Baltimore, MD and Jackson, MS, in order to reduce HIV rates among Black men.\",\n        \"_paragraph\": \"field_5eaa7b20baafc\",\n        \"graph1\": 487,\n        \"_graph1\": \"field_5eaa7b2cbaafd\",\n        \"graph_title1\": \"GAY & BISEXUAL MEN\",\n        \"_graph_title1\": \"field_5eac6625244c7\",\n        \"graph2\": 488,\n        \"_graph2\": \"field_5eaa7b51baafe\",\n        \"graph_title2\": \"AFRICAN AMERICAN<br>GAY & BISEXUAL MEN\",\n        \"_graph_title2\": \"field_5eac6631244c8\",\n        \"graph_caption\": \"may be diagnosed with HIV in their lifetime, if current rates persist.\",\n        \"_graph_caption\": \"field_5eaa7b5fbaaff\"\n    },\n    \"mode\": \"edit\"\n} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:acf/photo-left {\n    \"id\": \"block_5eaf001d67c1a\",\n    \"name\": \"acf\\/photo-left\",\n    \"data\": {\n        \"image\": 105,\n        \"_image\": \"field_5eaefea77a1ae\",\n        \"title\": \"education & intervention\",\n        \"_title\": \"field_5eaefec07a1af\",\n        \"paragraph\": \"While HIV-prevention interventions may include information about how to use a condom most effectively, they often fail to address the web of systemic and relational issues, such as stigma, discrimination, social inequities, interpersonal violence, and trauma, that underlie not only condom use behavior but overall sexual health behavior. They regularly are so focused on preventing initial HIV infection that they fail to include Black men who are living with HIV. Failing to meet the programming needs of people living with HIV serves to further isolate and stigmatize them, ultimately putting men at risk for poor health outcomes.\",\n        \"_paragraph\": \"field_5eaefec57a1b0\"\n    },\n    \"mode\": \"edit\"\n} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:acf/photo-left {\n    \"id\": \"block_5eaf00d867c1b\",\n    \"name\": \"acf\\/photo-left\",\n    \"data\": {\n        \"image\": 106,\n        \"_image\": \"field_5eaefea77a1ae\",\n        \"title\": \"engaging the community\",\n        \"_title\": \"field_5eaefec07a1af\",\n        \"paragraph\": \"ViiV Healthcare, Inc. created the <em>ACCELERATE!<\\/em> Initiative to address these gaps. ViiV recognized that in order to meet the needs of the communities most impacted by HIV, we all must look beyond an HIV diagnosis and consider people holistically.\\r\\n\\r\\n<strong>The voices from the communities most impacted by HIV, specifically Black MSM, are at the core of this project. The SWAG Toolkit was created by centering the needs of community members with the aim of enhancing their sexual well-being and overall quality of life.<\\/strong>\",\n        \"_paragraph\": \"field_5eaefec57a1b0\"\n    },\n    \"mode\": \"edit\"\n} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:acf/contact {\n    \"id\": \"block_5eaf118313f98\",\n    \"name\": \"acf\\/contact\",\n    \"data\": {\n        \"text\": \"Contact <a href=\\\"mailto:info@swagtoolkit.com\\\">info@swagtoolkit.com<\\/a> to learn how to bring SWAG to your community.\",\n        \"_text\": \"field_5eaf1080da2ce\"\n    },\n    \"mode\": \"edit\"\n} /-->', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-05-20 12:13:39', '2020-05-20 16:13:39', '', 2, 'http://staging.swagtoolkit.com/lesson-plans/2-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(534, 1, '2020-05-20 13:06:38', '2020-05-20 17:06:38', '<!-- wp:acf/top-resources {\n    \"id\": \"block_5eb3e56d15e5d\",\n    \"name\": \"acf\\/top-resources\",\n    \"data\": {\n        \"resources_0_title\": \"SWAG Toolkit Overview\",\n        \"_resources_0_title\": \"field_5eb3e4f9ce873\",\n        \"resources_0_cover\": 221,\n        \"_resources_0_cover\": \"field_5eb3e52ece874\",\n        \"resources_0_link\": \"\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2020\\/05\\/ISRC_SWAGOverview.pdf\",\n        \"_resources_0_link\": \"field_5eb3e541ce875\",\n        \"resources_1_title\": \"Community Agreements\",\n        \"_resources_1_title\": \"field_5eb3e4f9ce873\",\n        \"resources_1_cover\": 222,\n        \"_resources_1_cover\": \"field_5eb3e52ece874\",\n        \"resources_1_link\": \"\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2020\\/05\\/SWAG_Community-Agreements.pdf\",\n        \"_resources_1_link\": \"field_5eb3e541ce875\",\n        \"resources_2_title\": \"End-of-Session Evaluation\",\n        \"_resources_2_title\": \"field_5eb3e4f9ce873\",\n        \"resources_2_cover\": 223,\n        \"_resources_2_cover\": \"field_5eb3e52ece874\",\n        \"resources_2_link\": \"\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2020\\/05\\/ISRC_SWAGOverview.pdf\",\n        \"_resources_2_link\": \"field_5eb3e541ce875\",\n        \"resources\": 3,\n        \"_resources\": \"field_5eb3e4d7ce872\"\n    },\n    \"mode\": \"edit\"\n} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:acf/resources {\n    \"id\": \"block_5eb3f9743bb20\",\n    \"name\": \"acf\\/resources\",\n    \"data\": {\n        \"h2title\": \"Frequently Asked Questions\",\n        \"_h2title\": \"field_5eb3f54e1c1a0\",\n        \"paragraph\": \"\",\n        \"_paragraph\": \"field_5ebea9aa74d91\",\n        \"region_0_title\": \"I just found the SWAG Toolkit. Where should I start?\",\n        \"_region_0_title\": \"field_5eb3ae7556786\",\n        \"region_0_content\": \"There are several different places you can start with the SWAG Toolkit. If you are pressed for time, we recommend finding a lesson plan that addresses topics your group is interested in, review the lesson plan, and run the lesson to your group. If you have more time, we recommend visiting the <a href=\\\"\\/using-the-toolkit\\\">Using the Toolkit<\\/a> section of this site. If you are interested in the nuts and bolts of the toolkit, our downloadable <a href=\\\"\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2020\\/05\\/ISRC_SWAGOverview.pdf\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\" rel=\\\"noopener\\\">SWAG Toolkit Overview<\\/a> has details regarding our development process of the lesson plans.\",\n        \"_region_0_content\": \"field_5eb3ae7d56787\",\n        \"region_1_title\": \"My group isn’t engaged with the lessons; how can I get more discussion?\",\n        \"_region_1_title\": \"field_5eb3ae7556786\",\n        \"region_1_content\": \"There can be many reasons why a group isn’t engaged with lessons.\\r\\n\\r\\nFirstly, is the meeting taking place in a good environment? Is there enough space, is there a\\/c, is the space easy to get to for your group members? Discomfort with a space can hold people back from feeling safe enough to be open and share.\\r\\n\\r\\nSecondly, were you able to prepare and review the lessons beforehand? Group members will notice unprepared facilitators and may decide not to engage. Take some time and go over the material and plan questions or discussions the group could have.\\r\\n\\r\\nFinally, is there something going on in the world or the community that is more pressing? If there is something big going on your group might benefit from talking about that than the lesson plan.\",\n        \"_region_1_content\": \"field_5eb3ae7d56787\",\n        \"region_2_title\": \"I’m worried about not being able to answer my group’s questions. How do I prepare for knowledge focused lessons?\",\n        \"_region_2_title\": \"field_5eb3ae7556786\",\n        \"region_2_content\": \"You do not need to have all the answers when you run your session. However, if a question comes up about something you do not know, it is important to acknowledge that you do not know and offer to find out and report back. The lesson plans do have trainings on some basic topics for CECs and the SWAG website has resources, but you may need to use your network to find more detailed answers.\",\n        \"_region_2_content\": \"field_5eb3ae7d56787\",\n        \"region_3_title\": \"Since I am a part of the community how do I balance that with my role as a facilitator?\",\n        \"_region_3_title\": \"field_5eb3ae7556786\",\n        \"region_3_content\": \"It can be challenging to both serve and be a part of a community, but solid boundaries can help reduce some of that stress. Do not run groups with people you are friends with or dating as those relationships can unbalance group dynamics. Do not talk about group work when in the community. Avoid community drama, and if you feel like you need to step away for your own well-being, talk to your supervisor to switch out facilitators or come to a solution.\",\n        \"_region_3_content\": \"field_5eb3ae7d56787\",\n        \"region_4_title\": \"What makes a good facilitator?\",\n        \"_region_4_title\": \"field_5eb3ae7556786\",\n        \"region_4_content\": \"The SWAG Toolkit is less rigid than other lesson plans you may have run. While there are still knowledge and skills trainings in the lesson plans, our goal is for the lessons to facilitate connections and foster support among Black MSM.\\r\\n\\r\\nThis means that you will be discussing sensitive issues for individuals and the community. It is important to be empathic and reflectively listen to your group, both what they say and what they mean. You should seek clarification when you have a question and be willing to share power with group members. You should be flexible in the lessons. If you do not cover all of the material in a lesson or if the group begins discussing another topic, that is okay. As long as the group is discussing issues related to Black MSM, members can continue to develop.\\r\\n\\r\\nFinally, be sure to take care of yourself. If you are too tired, too stressed, or unprepared the meetings may not be as beneficial. It is just as important to look after yourself as it is to support others.\",\n        \"_region_4_content\": \"field_5eb3ae7d56787\",\n        \"region\": 5,\n        \"_region\": \"field_5eb3ae4756785\",\n        \"promo_box_title\": \"\",\n        \"_promo_box_title\": \"field_5ebea9fa74d93\",\n        \"promo_box_text\": \"\",\n        \"_promo_box_text\": \"field_5ebeaa0c74d94\",\n        \"promo_box_email\": \"\",\n        \"_promo_box_email\": \"field_5ebeaa1874d95\",\n        \"promo_box\": \"\",\n        \"_promo_box\": \"field_5ebea9d174d92\"\n    },\n    \"mode\": \"edit\"\n} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Facilitating Lessons', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '15-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-05-20 13:06:38', '2020-05-20 17:06:38', '', 15, 'http://staging.swagtoolkit.com/lesson-plans/15-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(535, 1, '2020-05-20 13:06:39', '2020-05-20 17:06:39', '<!-- wp:acf/top-resources {\n    \"id\": \"block_5eb3e56d15e5d\",\n    \"name\": \"acf\\/top-resources\",\n    \"data\": {\n        \"resources_0_title\": \"SWAG Toolkit Overview\",\n        \"_resources_0_title\": \"field_5eb3e4f9ce873\",\n        \"resources_0_cover\": 221,\n        \"_resources_0_cover\": \"field_5eb3e52ece874\",\n        \"resources_0_link\": \"\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2020\\/05\\/ISRC_SWAGOverview.pdf\",\n        \"_resources_0_link\": \"field_5eb3e541ce875\",\n        \"resources_1_title\": \"Community Agreements\",\n        \"_resources_1_title\": \"field_5eb3e4f9ce873\",\n        \"resources_1_cover\": 222,\n        \"_resources_1_cover\": \"field_5eb3e52ece874\",\n        \"resources_1_link\": \"\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2020\\/05\\/SWAG_Community-Agreements.pdf\",\n        \"_resources_1_link\": \"field_5eb3e541ce875\",\n        \"resources_2_title\": \"End-of-Session Evaluation\",\n        \"_resources_2_title\": \"field_5eb3e4f9ce873\",\n        \"resources_2_cover\": 223,\n        \"_resources_2_cover\": \"field_5eb3e52ece874\",\n        \"resources_2_link\": \"\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2020\\/05\\/ISRC_SWAGOverview.pdf\",\n        \"_resources_2_link\": \"field_5eb3e541ce875\",\n        \"resources\": 3,\n        \"_resources\": \"field_5eb3e4d7ce872\"\n    },\n    \"mode\": \"edit\"\n} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:acf/resources {\n    \"id\": \"block_5eb3f9743bb20\",\n    \"name\": \"acf\\/resources\",\n    \"data\": {\n        \"h2title\": \"Frequently Asked Questions\",\n        \"_h2title\": \"field_5eb3f54e1c1a0\",\n        \"paragraph\": \"\",\n        \"_paragraph\": \"field_5ebea9aa74d91\",\n        \"region_0_title\": \"I just found the SWAG Toolkit. Where should I start?\",\n        \"_region_0_title\": \"field_5eb3ae7556786\",\n        \"region_0_content\": \"There are several different places you can start with the SWAG Toolkit. If you are pressed for time, we recommend finding a lesson plan that addresses topics your group is interested in, review the lesson plan, and run the lesson to your group. If you have more time, we recommend visiting the <a href=\\\"\\/using-the-toolkit\\\">Using the Toolkit<\\/a> section of this site. If you are interested in the nuts and bolts of the toolkit, our downloadable <a href=\\\"\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2020\\/05\\/ISRC_SWAGOverview.pdf\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\" rel=\\\"noopener\\\">SWAG Toolkit Overview<\\/a> has details regarding our development process of the lesson plans.\",\n        \"_region_0_content\": \"field_5eb3ae7d56787\",\n        \"region_1_title\": \"My group isn’t engaged with the lessons; how can I get more discussion?\",\n        \"_region_1_title\": \"field_5eb3ae7556786\",\n        \"region_1_content\": \"There can be many reasons why a group isn’t engaged with lessons.\\r\\n\\r\\nFirstly, is the meeting taking place in a good environment? Is there enough space, is there a\\/c, is the space easy to get to for your group members? Discomfort with a space can hold people back from feeling safe enough to be open and share.\\r\\n\\r\\nSecondly, were you able to prepare and review the lessons beforehand? Group members will notice unprepared facilitators and may decide not to engage. Take some time and go over the material and plan questions or discussions the group could have.\\r\\n\\r\\nFinally, is there something going on in the world or the community that is more pressing? If there is something big going on your group might benefit from talking about that than the lesson plan.\",\n        \"_region_1_content\": \"field_5eb3ae7d56787\",\n        \"region_2_title\": \"I’m worried about not being able to answer my group’s questions. How do I prepare for knowledge focused lessons?\",\n        \"_region_2_title\": \"field_5eb3ae7556786\",\n        \"region_2_content\": \"You do not need to have all the answers when you run your session. However, if a question comes up about something you do not know, it is important to acknowledge that you do not know and offer to find out and report back. The lesson plans do have trainings on some basic topics for CECs and the SWAG website has resources, but you may need to use your network to find more detailed answers.\",\n        \"_region_2_content\": \"field_5eb3ae7d56787\",\n        \"region_3_title\": \"Since I am a part of the community how do I balance that with my role as a facilitator?\",\n        \"_region_3_title\": \"field_5eb3ae7556786\",\n        \"region_3_content\": \"It can be challenging to both serve and be a part of a community, but solid boundaries can help reduce some of that stress. Do not run groups with people you are friends with or dating as those relationships can unbalance group dynamics. Do not talk about group work when in the community. Avoid community drama, and if you feel like you need to step away for your own well-being, talk to your supervisor to switch out facilitators or come to a solution.\",\n        \"_region_3_content\": \"field_5eb3ae7d56787\",\n        \"region_4_title\": \"What makes a good facilitator?\",\n        \"_region_4_title\": \"field_5eb3ae7556786\",\n        \"region_4_content\": \"The SWAG Toolkit is less rigid than other lesson plans you may have run. While there are still knowledge and skills trainings in the lesson plans, our goal is for the lessons to facilitate connections and foster support among Black MSM.\\r\\n\\r\\nThis means that you will be discussing sensitive issues for individuals and the community. It is important to be empathic and reflectively listen to your group, both what they say and what they mean. You should seek clarification when you have a question and be willing to share power with group members. You should be flexible in the lessons. If you do not cover all of the material in a lesson or if the group begins discussing another topic, that is okay. As long as the group is discussing issues related to Black MSM, members can continue to develop.\\r\\n\\r\\nFinally, be sure to take care of yourself. If you are too tired, too stressed, or unprepared the meetings may not be as beneficial. It is just as important to look after yourself as it is to support others.\",\n        \"_region_4_content\": \"field_5eb3ae7d56787\",\n        \"region\": 5,\n        \"_region\": \"field_5eb3ae4756785\",\n        \"promo_box_title\": \"\",\n        \"_promo_box_title\": \"field_5ebea9fa74d93\",\n        \"promo_box_text\": \"\",\n        \"_promo_box_text\": \"field_5ebeaa0c74d94\",\n        \"promo_box_email\": \"\",\n        \"_promo_box_email\": \"field_5ebeaa1874d95\",\n        \"promo_box\": \"\",\n        \"_promo_box\": \"field_5ebea9d174d92\"\n    },\n    \"mode\": \"edit\"\n} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Facilitating Lessons', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '15-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-05-20 13:06:39', '2020-05-20 17:06:39', '', 15, 'http://staging.swagtoolkit.com/lesson-plans/15-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
